Publishing to RStudio Connect using Github Actions and renv

Ian Flores Siaca

When we want to publish a data artifact to RStudio Connect we have three main routes we can follow. The first one is following a button deployment process, which means within the IDE you establish your credentials, you press publish at the top right corner of your source code pane, and voila! You have your content available in Connect.

The second route we can follow is a Git-backed deployment from within the Connect interface. To do this, we log in into our account and on the drop down in the main panel select the option Import from Git and follow the process to connect our Git repository to Connect.

However this process has some caveats. If we want to publish private Git repositories, we need to add a service account to the repositories and add the credentials of this service account into the Connect configuration file. Another caveat is the fact that you can’t execute tests before publishing your artifact because it will assume that the version that it is fetching is ready for production use. This is where GitHub Actions come into play.

GitHub Actions is a tool from GitHub that allows us to automate workflows, test our software and build images or packages as needed, meaning that it acts as a CI/CD tool. One of the benefits of using Actions is that it allows us to integrate tests into our deployment pipeline to Connect, we can publish from private repositories without having to manage a service account, and we get the benefits of Continuous Deployment.

Now that we understand why we want to use GitHub Actions and their benefits let’s discuss an example to showcase how to use them. In this example we will be testing a Shiny App and then publishing it to Connect. To simplify the package management of the environment we use the renv package. It is useful in terms of reproducibility because it will save the package version and from what repository you installed the package so that you can restore the environment in other computers. You can read more about renv here. Below you can see how our files are organized in the repository, and you can access them here.

As you can see the app lives in the app/ directory, and within this directory lives the tests of the app as well. However, our main file of interest lives in .github/workflows/deploy_to_connect.yml and it specifies the workflow we want to run today. We will review the contents of the GitHub Action file so you understand what is going on.

On the first five lines we specify what event triggers this actions to run. Here we are specifying that whenever there is a push to the main or master branches, the jobs specified in this action will run.

on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main
      - master

On these lines, we specify on which OS we want to run our job annd the environment variables. Note that within the env key, we have specified variables in two ways. One of them being just specifying the variable argument and the other one is using the mechanism of GitHub secrets. These secrets are a method that GitHub offers to manage sensitive information or credentials in a secure manner without having to expose it. To access them we use the secrets keyword and then the name of the variable we want to access.

jobs:
  deploy-to-connect:
    runs-on: macOS-latest
    env:
      APP_NAME: "GHA_SHINYTEST_RSC"
      APP_DIR: "app"
      GITHUB_PAT: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}
      RSCONNECT_URL: ${{ secrets.RSCONNECT_URL }}
      RSCONNECT_USERNAME: ${{ secrets.RSCONNECT_USERNAME }}
      RSCONNECT_APIKEY: ${{ secrets.RSCONNECT_APIKEY }}

You can specify your secrets in the settings panel of your repository.

Now that we have specified the necessary information to setup our environment, we now have to specify what does our job actually do. We do this under the steps key and each entry it’s treated as a different step to the job. The first step is checking out the files of the repository so that we have them available to 1) install the packages we need for our app to run and 2) deploy the actual app to RStudio Connect. The second step is setting up R. For these two steps we use actions that already exist and that’s why we use the uses key.

    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v2

      - uses: r-lib/actions/setup-r@master

In these next two steps we install renv and restore our environment. Restoring our environment means installing the packages listed in the renv.lock file with their dependencies and matching versions. One thing to note here is that we specify what we want to run in the run key and then on the shell key we specify what program will execute the run key content and pass it as an argument.

      - name: Install renv
        run: |
          install.packages("renv")
        shell: Rscript {0}

      - name: Restore environment
        run: |
          renv::restore()
        shell: Rscript {0}

After restoring our environment and having the necessary packages installed, we now want to execute the shinytests we have developed in order to see if our app is ready for publishing. In order to use shinytest we first have to install some dependencies in our environment, which is what we do in the first step. After we have these dependencies installed we execute our tests, if they are successful we can move on to dealing with RStudio Connect. If they are not successful the job will fail and you will have to review your app.

      - name: Install shinytest dependencies
        run: |
          shinytest::installDependencies()
        shell: Rscript {0}

      - name: Run shinytest tests
        run: |
          shinytest::testApp("${{ env.APP_DIR }}")
        shell: Rscript {0}

Once our tests are completed successfully we will move into authenticating ourselves with the RStudio Connect server. To interact with RStudio Connect we will use the rsconnect package. We first register which RStudio Connect server we will be interacting with, and then provide the credentials for the specific user that will be publishing into the platform.

      - name: Authenticate with RStudio Connect
        run: |
          rsconnect::addConnectServer(url = "${{ env.RSCONNECT_URL}}",
                            name = "rsc_server")
          rsconnect::connectApiUser(account = "${{ env.RSCONNECT_USERNAME }}",
                          server = "rsc_server",
                          apiKey = "${{ env.RSCONNECT_APIKEY }}",
                          quiet = FALSE)
        shell: Rscript {0}

As a final step, after authenticating, we deploy our app using the deployApp function. This will create the manifest.json file, bundle the application and push the bundle to RStudio Connect. Notice that we are using the argument forceUpdate set to TRUE, this is because we want the application to re-update in RStudio Connect every time the job gets to this point.

      - name: Deploy app
        run: |
          rsconnect::deployApp(appDir = "${{ env.APP_DIR }}",
                     appName = "${{ env.APP_NAME }}",
                     account = "${{ env.RSCONNECT_USERNAME }}",
                     server = "rsc_server",
                     forceUpdate = TRUE)
        shell: Rscript {0}

Now that we have showcased how to deploy your data products into RStudio Connect using GitHub Actions we hope that publishing these products from private GitHub repositories will be easier to manage for data scientists.

All the code for the application and the GitHub Actions is available at this repo: https://github.com/ian-flores/gha-deployment-connect-private-repo
